Omaha Public Schools Health and Safety
September 10 at 7:24 PM ·

This pandemic has been hard on many, but there are resources for help.

A CDC report shows that there are raised concerns about mental health and substance abuse during COVID-19.

Sept. 10 is World Suicide Prevention Day and September is Suicide Prevention Month.

If you know someone who is hurting, please make a call to one of these hot lines:
• The Suicide Prevention Lifeline and Veteran’s Suicide Prevention Lifeline at
1-800-273-8255.
• The Nebraska Family Helpline at 1-888-866-8660.
• The Nebraska Rural Response Hotline at 1-800-464-0258.

Omaha Public Schools Community, we're happy to share this month's podcast with Superintendent Dr. Logan.

We update our 1 to 1 technology initiative and our work to monitor health conditions in our community. Those conditions play a vital role in our decision-making and how we will proceed beyond this first quarter of our school year. We will continue to communicate with and update our families as early as possible once decisions are made.

Thank you to Edison Elementary for hosting us!

post_text:
We are excited to officially begin the 2020 school year with our students! As we start in the 100% remote learning instructional model, we know that many families still have questions. Schools are ready and eager to assist by phone and email.

Starting today, Aug. 18 through Friday, Aug. 21, we also have three Family Support Centers available for questions that need in-person assistance. These sites provide a one-stop shop to help families get the school year off to a successful start. Families will be able to work with nutrition services, technology support staff, counselors and other staff to answer any questions they may have.

Support Centers will be open from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. at Skinner Magnet Center, Beveridge Magnet Middle and Bryan Middle School. Please see your email for more details.

post_text:
As we continue to prepare for a responsible return to school, Omaha Public Schools' team is getting ready in many ways including today's test run for transportation. 🚍

Drivers practiced their routes and reviewed safety measures. In addition to standard bus protocol, riders will see new signage, hand sanitizing stations, social distancing, face coverings and enhanced cleaning measures. We want our families to know that our staff is prepared to start school in-person next week.

We've shared that plans may need to change as conditions evolve. We have planned for on-site, Family 3/2 and fully at-home instruction, we encourage families to do the same. If changes are necessary, we will communicate through email, by phone, and official online platforms.

If you have questions specific to busing, contact the Transportation Hotline at 531-299-0140, or visit bit.ly/3kb6TwV.

post_text:
On Friday July 17th, America lost two great champions for civil rights. Omaha Public Schools would like to join the nation in honoring the legacy of these leaders, Rep. John Lewis and the Rev. C.T. Vivian.

Both, Rev. Vivian and Rep. Lewis, were voting rights advocates and worked alongside Martin Luther King Jr. to bring racial injustices to light and change policies to make the U.S. more inclusive.

OPS aims to continue in their legacy by providing a space in all our American Government classes for students to register to vote. In addition, we have moved to reserve Election Day as a day off of school and work to encourage our staff, students, and families to take advantage of the opportunities that Rep. Lewis and Rev. Vivian sacrificed so much for us all to have.

Our high school libraries also have copies of Rep. Lewis' young adult novel "March" for students who may want to learn more about his impact. To learn more about the civil rights movement in Omaha please visit: https://invisiblehistory.ops.org/Default.aspx

post_text: Omaha Public Schools wants to thank all staff and friends who have helped donate to Food Bank for the Heartland during this difficult time. We are grateful for the work they do every day to help families across our community. To support that work, we invited staff to donate regularly through 2020. Hundreds of people joined in, totaling more than $70,000 pledged through the months to come. We know many friends of our district are donating, too, recognizing the need during this time. To everyone, we say THANK YOU!
text: Omaha Public Schools wants to thank all staff and friends who have helped donate to Food Bank for the Heartland during this difficult time. We are grateful for the work they do every day to help families across our community. To support that work, we invited staff to donate regularly through 2020. Hundreds of people joined in, totaling more than $70,000 pledged through the months to come. We know many friends of our district are donating, too, recognizing the need during this time. To everyone, we say THANK YOU!

post_text: Food Bank for the Heartland and The Salvation Army of Omaha are launching a mobile BackPack program for students across our community! We appreciate their partnership to help meet this community-wide need. Please see their post for full details.
shared_text:
Food Bank for the Heartland
March 19 at 3:15 PM ·

Food Bank for the Heartland is partnering with Westside Nutritional Services, The Salvation Army of Omaha, Saving Grace Perishable Food Rescue and local school districts to launch the Mobile BackPack program. The program will distribute 26,000 meals each week!

We will deliver free meal bags to 13 sites starting Friday, March 20. Each meal bag contains five breakfasts and five lunches including milk and fresh produce for a total of 10 meals. A meal bag will be offered for each child in a household.
https://foodbankheartland.org/covid-19/

**Please note**
Starting Tuesday, March 31, children must be present to receive meals. Food Bank for the Heartland has to make this change to adhere to federal regulations for child feeding sites.

post_text:
This announcement was just made from The College Board.

In response to the rapidly evolving situation around the coronavirus (COVID-19), the College Board is canceling the May 2, 2020, SAT administration. Makeup exams for the March 14 administration (scheduled March 28) are also canceled. Registered students will receive refunds.
The College Board will provide future additional SAT testing opportunities for students as soon as feasible in place of canceled administrations.
During this challenging time, our focus will remain on the health and safety of students. We will be flexible, thoughtful, and collaborative in exploring ways to continue to support student learning and provide opportunities to test.
More details: http://spr.ly/61861subu.

This weekend, South High Magnet is partnering with Beveridge Magnet Middle for the 10th Annual CultureFest with the help of University of Nebraska at Omaha's Service Learning Academy.

The public event is open to anyone interested in exploring cultural diversity.

There will be performances, exhibits, hands-on activities, dancing, and food.

The event is at the Milo Bail Student Center from 2 - 4 p.m. Sunday.

post_text: Check out what Beals Elementary School is doing to go above and beyond!
shared_text:
Beals Elementary School
February 11 at 9:42 PM ·

Last week, our Beals staff collected donations for various agencies around Omaha! This is an annual event called "Winter Blues and Blahs" where our staff gives back to the community to uplift our spirits during the cold and dark winter months.
Places like...The Siena Francis House, St. Vincent de Paul, Open Door Mission, Project Harmony, and NE Humane Society will receive our donations. It feels so great to help out our amazing community! Thank you to everyone who participated! Your items are greatly appreciated!

post_text: Way to go Crestridge Magnet Center!
shared_text:
Crestridge Magnet Center
February 12 at 5:20 PM ·

From Our Partners at DIBS For Kids- Congratulations to all of you and your wonderful students! Your DIBS kids have taken home and read 15,000 books so far this school year. Lined up end to end this many books would be as long as 30 football fields. Nice work Crestridge Vikings!

De parte de nuestros socios en DIBS For Kids ¡Felicitaciones a todos ustedes y sus maravillosos estudiantes! Sus hijos DIBS se han llevado a casa y leyeron 15,000 libros en lo que va del año escolar. Alineados de principio a fin, esta cantidad de libros duraría hasta 30 campos de fútbol. Buen trabajo Crestridge Vikingos!

It's African Heritage and Health Week!

The fourth recipe to try is called Pilau from Zanzibar.

Similar to pilaf, rice is cooked within a mixture of spices (garlic, ginger, cumin, cardamon, cloves, cinnamon, herbs), fried onions, broth, and a selected set of meat or vegetables. The ingredients are cooked within the rice, all in the very same pot.
